A regional government may adopt its own name.

1. The composition of a regional assembly shall be prescribed by Act of Parliament and shall consist of-
directly elected representatives elected on the basis of universal adult suffrage at elections conducted by the Electoral Commission;
representatives of women, who shall not be less than one third of the membership;
representatives of the youth and persons with disabilities;
representatives of indigenous cultural interests in areas where there is a traditional or cultural leader, nominated by the traditional or cultural leader but not exceeding fifteen per cent of the members of the regional assembly;
district chairpersons in the region who shall be ex-officio members with no right to vote.
2. directly elected representatives elected on the basis of universal adult suffrage at elections conducted by the Electoral Commission;
3. representatives of women, who shall not be less than one third of the membership;
4. representatives of the youth and persons with disabilities;
5. representatives of indigenous cultural interests in areas where there is a traditional or cultural leader, nominated by the traditional or cultural leader but not exceeding fifteen per cent of the members of the regional assembly;
6. district chairpersons in the region who shall be ex-officio members with no right to vote.
7. A regional assembly shall have a speaker elected by the regional assembly from among its members; but a person shall only be taken to have been elected if the votes cast in his or her favour are more than fifty percent of all the members of the regional assembly.
8. The speaker of the regional assembly shall, in relation to the regional assembly, perform similar functions to those of the Speaker of Parliament.
9. Members of regional assemblies shall serve for the same term as members of district councils.
